        {
            "block_label": "text",
            "block_content": "Model quantization methods. Quantization reduces the bit-precision of deep learning models (Han et al., 2016; Jacob et al., 2018; Nagel et al., 2019; Wang et al., 2019; Nagel et al., 2020; Lin et al., 2020), which helps to reduce the model size and accelerate inference. Quantization techniques generally fall into two categories: quantization-aware training (QAT, which relies on backpropagation to update the quantized weights) (Bengio et al., 2013; Gholami et al., 2021; Nagel et al., 2021; Choi et al., 2018) and post-training quantization (Jacob et al., 2018; Nagel et al., 2019; 2020) (PTQ, usually training-free). The QAT methods cannot easily scale up to large models like LLMs. Therefore, people usually use PTQ methods to quantize LLMs.",
            "block_bbox": [
                608,
                531,
                1088,
                844
            ],
            "block_id": 7,
            "block_order": 7,
            "group_id": 7,
            "block_polygon_points": [
                [
                    608.0,
                    531.0
                ],
                [
                    1088.0,
                    531.0
                ],
                [
                    1088.0,
                    844.0
                ],
                [
                    608.0,
                    844.0
                ]
            ]
        },
        {
            "block_label": "text",
            "block_content": "Quantization of LLMs. People study two settings for LLM quantization: (1) W8A8 quantization, where both activation and weights are quantized to INT8 (Dettmers et al., 2022; Xiao et al., 2022; Yao et al., 2022; Wei et al., 2022a; 2023); (2) Low-bit weight-only quantization (e.g., W4A16), where only weights are quantized into low-bit integers (Frantar et al., 2022; Dettmers & Zettlemoyer, 2022; Sheng et al., 2023; Park et al., 2022). We focus on the second setting in this work since it not only reduces the hardware barrier (requiring a smaller memory size) but also speeds up the token generation (remedies memory-bound workload). Apart from the vanilla round-to-nearest baseline (RTN), GPTQ (Frantar et al., 2022) is the closest to our work. However, the reconstruction process of GPTQ leads to an over-fitting issue to the calibration set and may not preserve the generalist abilities of LLMs for other modalities and domains. It also requires a reordering trick to work for some models (e.g., LLaMA-7B (Touvron et al., 2023a) and OPT-66B (Zhang et al., 2022)). Apart from quantization methods designed for general-purpose hardware, SpAtten (Wang et al., 2020) designs a progressive approach to gradually increase the number of bits used in softmax calculation.",
            "block_bbox": [
